  "prompt": "What does it mean when you have blood clots but no period?",
  "response": "It's important to note that I am not a medical professional, but I can provide some general information. Having blood clots but no menstrual period can be concerning and may be caused by various factors. Some potential reasons include:\n\n1. **Hormonal Imbalances**: Hormonal fluctuations can sometimes lead to irregular menstrual cycles and cause unusual bleeding or spotting with blood clots.\n\n2. **Uterine Fibroids**: These are non-cancerous growths in the uterus that can cause heavy menstrual bleeding, spotting, and blood clots.\n\n3. **Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)**: This condition can cause irregular periods, spotting, and blood clots due to hormonal imbalances.\n\n4. **Endometriosis**: This condition involves the growth of endometrial tissue outside the uterus, which can cause irregular bleeding and blood clots.\n\n5. **Miscarriage**: In some cases, blood clots and no period could be an indication of a miscarriage, especially if pregnancy was suspected or confirmed.\n\n6. **Infection**: Pelvic infections can sometimes cause bleeding and clotting outside of the regular menstrual cycle.\n\n7. **Medications**: Certain medications, such as blood thinners or hormonal treatments, can affect menstrual bleeding patterns.\n\n8. **Stress**: High levels of stress can impact hormonal balance and menstrual cycles.\n\nIf you are experiencing these symptoms, it is important to consult with a healthcare provider for a thorough evaluation and appropriate diagnosis. They can provide personalized insight based on your medical history and symptoms.",
